{{Infobox military conflict |conflict=Siege of Bristol |image= |caption= |partof=[[English Civil War]] |date=23 August – 10 September 1645 |place=[[Bristol]] |result=Decisive Parliamentary victory |combatant1=[[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]] |combatant2=[[Cavalier|Royalist]]s |commander1=[[Thomas Fairfax, 3rd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Lord Fairfax]] |commander2=[[Prince Rupert]] |strength1= |strength2= |casualties1= |casualties2= |}} {{Campaignbox First English Civil War}}
The '''second siege of Bristol''' of the [[English Civil War]] lasted from 23 August 1645 until 10 September 1645, when the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] commander [[Prince Rupert]] surrendered the city he had [[Siege of Bristol (1643)|captured from the Parliamentarians]] on 26 July 1643 to [[Thomas Fairfax, 3rd Lord Fairfax of Cameron|Lord Fairfax]] the commander of Parliament's [[New Model Army]].
==Prelude== Fairfax and the New Model Army, after reducing [[Bridgwater]], had turned back to clear away the [[Dorsetshire]] [[Clubmen]] and to besiege [[Sherborne Castle]]. On the completion of this task, it had been decided to besiege Bristol.{{sfn|Atkinson|1911|loc=41. Fall of Bristol}}
==Siege== On 23 August 1645 the New Model Army [[investment (military)|invested]] Bristol.{{sfn|Atkinson|1911|loc=41. Fall of Bristol}} On the night of 9/10 September, Fairfax's army stormed Bristol. [[Prince Rupert]] had long realised the hopelessness of further fighting, the very summons to surrender sent in by Fairfax placed the fate of Bristol on the political issue, the lines of defence around the place were too extensive for his small force, and on 10 September he surrendered Bristol on terms. He was escorted to Oxford with his men, conversing as he rode with the officers of the escort about peace and the future of his adopted country.{{sfn|Atkinson|1911|loc=41. Fall of Bristol}}
==Aftermath== King [[Charles I of England|Charles I]], almost stunned by the suddenness of the catastrophic loss of Bristol, dismissed Rupert (his nephew) from all his offices and ordered him to leave England. The fall of Bristol meant that Chester was the only important seaport remaining to connect the English Royalists with Ireland.{{sfn|Atkinson|1911|loc=41. Fall of Bristol}}
